<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900423-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>900423-0048.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   A U.S. HOSTAGE WAS RELEASED by pro-Iranian kidnappers inLebanon.   After nearly 39 months in captivity, educator RobertPolhill was freed in Beirut by Islamic Jihad for theLiberation of Palestine, a group that holds at least twoother Americans. Polhill, who was taken to Syria beforeheading to West Germany, was the first American captive to bereleased in almost three-and-a-half years. The 55-year-oldNew Yorker said he was &quot;happy and grateful&quot; about hisrelease, but expressed concern about those still held. Bushthanked Syria and Iran for their roles in winning Polhill'sfreedom, and called for the release of all hostages.</LP><TEXT>   The terms of Polhill's release, which followed a series ofcommuniques from the extremists, weren't known. At least 17foreigners are missing in Lebanon.   ---   MILLIONS OF PEOPLE MARKED Earth Day with rallies aroundthe globe.   An estimated 200 million people in 140 nations on allseven continents joined events dedicated to preserving theenvironment. More than 3,600 U.S. communities staged programsto commemorate the 20th anniversary of the Earth Dayanti-pollution movement, cleaning beaches and planting trees.About 100,000 people gathered in Washington to hearenvironmental activists, and thousands watched a balloondecorated as the Earth rise in New York City.   Bush expressed support for a tanker-free zone offFlorida's coast and indicated that a decision on offshore oildrilling would be made &quot;very soon.&quot;   ---   A Communist official in Moscow warned that Lithuania'sindependence drive is leading the Baltic republic tocatastrophe, but denied that the Kremlin had imposed a totaleconomic blockade. In Vilnius, officials reaffirmed theirsecessionist stand and sent the Soviet premier a list ofitems that Lithuania may cease supplying to Soviet industry.                                                                                                          The White House is moving to curtail planned investmentand trade assistance to the Soviet Union in the wake ofMoscow's efforts to crush Lithuania's independence bid, Bushadministration officials said.   ---   Voters in Croatia cast ballots in the Yugoslav republic'sfirst free multiparty elections since before World War II.The Communists, who have ruled for 45 years, were facing achallenge from a center-right coalition and a nationalistparty with separatist leanings. Neighboring Slovenians alsovoted in elections to choose a regional president.   ---   Pope John Paul II announced plans to convene anunprecedented meeting of Europe's bishops to discuss theRoman Catholic Church's role on the Continent after thecollapse of Communist governments. The pontiff, who alsointends to visit Cuba in December, made his remarks at theconclusion of a two-day visit to Czechoslovakia.   ---   Nigeria's military government said it crushed a coupattempt after heavy fighting against rebel troops in Lagos.The rebellion was launched by junior officers seeking thebreakup of the African country's federation of 19 states inan effort to end Moslem domination. Casualty figures weren'tdisclosed.   ---   Mandela called for an intensified armed struggle againstSouth Africa's white minority government to spur talks to endapartheid. Speaking in Transkei, the black nationalist alsosaid he would appeal for tougher anti-apartheid curbs when hemeets with Britain's Thatcher, probably July 6.   ---   Israel acknowledged that it had secretly co-financed aJewish settlement in the Christian quarter of Jerusalem'swalled Old City, leasing a building owned by the GreekOrthodox Church through a Panamanian company. Israel said itpaid $1.8 million toward the settlement of 150 Jews, whichsparked strikes and violent protests.   ---   Solidarity urged Poland to accelerate the pace ofpolitical and economic restructuring. In a resolution,approved at a national congress in Gdansk, the trade unionalso demanded new elections by early 1991 to remove Communistholdovers from office.   ---   China's Premier Li is scheduled to travel today to theSoviet Union for talks aimed at solidifying recently restoredties between the two Communist nations. Moscow and Beijingare expected to reach agreement on troop withdrawals alongthe Sino-Soviet border during the trip by Li, the most seniorChinese official to visit Moscow since 1964.   ---   India's Prime Minister Singh warned Pakistan againstfomenting trouble on the border. He made his statementsfollowing a clash Saturday between Indian and Pakistanitroops in the disputed region of Kashmir, where Moslemseparatists have been waging a pro-independence campaign.   ---   Died: Erte, 97, Russian-born artist known for his art decopainting, sculpture and theatrical design, Saturday, inParis.</TEXT></DOC>